### Computational Intelligence

This is a journal. A vessel for ideas, supposedly. It’s supposed to be about [computer science](/Computer_science) and [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence). A place where minds supposedly collide, producing something... intelligent. But right now, it reads like a faded photograph, a memory of what it might have been.

#### Academic Journal

It masquerades as an academic journal, a peer-reviewed sanctuary for the rigorously examined. It claims to cover research on [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence) and [computer science](/Computer_science). Novel research, innovative applications – these are the words they use. Like a promise whispered in the dark, easily broken. It’s meant to be a broad spectrum, you see. From [machine learning](/Machine_learning) – that relentless pursuit of algorithms that mimic thought – to [knowledge mining](/Knowledge_mining), digging through mountains of data for a single, glittering nugget. Then there's [web intelligence](/Web_intelligence), the chaotic symphony of the internet, and [AI language](/AI_language), the struggle to make machines understand the nuances of human speech. And, of course, the philosophical implications – the existential dread that comes with creating something that might, one day, surpass us.

#### Publication Details

Established in 1985. A lifetime ago, in the grand scheme of things. Published by [Wiley-Blackwell](/Wiley-Blackwell), a name that sounds as solid and unyielding as its publications. Quarterly. Four times a year, they release these pronouncements. Like clockwork. Or perhaps, like a slow, deliberate march towards an inevitable conclusion. Diane Inkpen, the current [editor-in-chief](/Editors-in-chief). A gatekeeper, I suppose. Deciding what gets in, what gets… filtered.

The journal’s worth, as they measure it – these metrics, these [impact factors](/Impact_factor) – they’re just numbers. In 2022, [Scopus](/Scopus) gave it a CiteScore of 5.3. A number. [Clarivate](/Clarivate)’s [Web of Science](/Web_of_Science) offered a [Journal Citation Indicator](/Journal_Citation_Indicator) of 0.39 and a [Journal Impact Factor](/Journal_Impact_Factor) of 2.8. They’re trying to quantify relevance, to assign value to the intangible. It’s a futile exercise, really. Like trying to bottle smoke.

